The '''''Vénus de Quinipily''''' ({{IPA-fr|venys də kinipili}}, {{lang-br|Ar groareg Houarn/Groah Hoart}}, {{lang-en|The Iron Lady}}) is an ancient statue of uncertain origins, located southeast of [[Baud, Morbihan]], [[Brittany]], in north–western France. It is approximately 2.2 metres (7.2 ft) in height and carved from [[granite]]. The statue represents a naked woman and stands in front of a fountain on a 2.75 m high granite pedestal. The large basin beneath the statue is also carved out of a single granite block. It is believed that the statue may be of Greek, Roman or Egyptian origin. There is similar uncertainty about its subject; it may be a [[Celtic deities|Celtic deity]], the Roman [[Mother goddess]] [[Cybele]], or an [[Isis#Classical Egyptian period|Egyptian Isis statue]].

It was originally erected at the site of a former Roman camp in Castennec in [[Bieuzy|Bieuzy-les-Eaux]], a commune in the [[Morbihan]] [[Departments of France|department]] in Brittany. It was the centre of superstitious rites in Brittany for centuries and became an object of a [[Paganism|pagan veneration]]. At the request of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Vannes|Bishop of Vannes]], the statue was thrown into the [[Blavet]] river twice; first in 1661 and then again in 1670, but recovered both times, first in 1664 and then in 1695 by [[Pierre de Lannion]], the Lord of Blavet Quinipily. In 1701, the statue was substantially altered and placed in its present position at Quinipily where a garden has been created to showpiece the ancient monument.

The statue is classified under [[Monument historique]]{{snd}}a National Heritage Site of France on August 24, 1993. The heritage protection was made applicable from November 18, 1943. It is indexed in the [[Base Mérimée]]{{snd}}a database of architectural heritage maintained by the [[Minister of Culture (France)|French Ministry of Culture]].

==History==

===Origin===
The origins of the Vénus de Quinipily are uncertain, but it is believed to have been sculpted around 49 BC. It was originally erected at the site of a former Roman camp in Castennec in [[Bieuzy|Bieuzy-les-Eaux]], a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Morbihan]] [[Departments of France|department]] in [[Brittany]] in northwestern France.<ref name="govfr">{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00091021|title=Monuments historiques|trans_title=Historic Monuments|language=French|accessdate=April 20, 2014|publisher=[[Minister of Culture (France)|French Ministry of Culture and Communication]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504204601/http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00091021|archivedate=4 May 2014}}</ref> Various origins of the statue have been proposed, including Greek, Roman or Egyptian; a [[Celtic deities|Celtic deity]], the Roman [[Mother goddess]] [[Cybele]], or an [[Isis#Classical Egyptian period|Egyptian Isis statue]].{{sfn|Ward|2003|p=330}}{{sfn|Monk Kidd|Kidd Taylor|2009|p=142}}{{sfn|Douglas-Cooper|Mellor|2000|p=14}} It has also been proposed that the statue did not survive its restoration in 1696 by Pierre de Lannion, the Lord of Blavet Quinipily, and that he secretly replaced it with a new one.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}}{{sfn|Murray-Aynsley|1900|p=87}} According to the French archaeologist Monsieur de Penhouët, the statue was built by [[Moors|Moorish]] soldiers in the Roman army.{{sfn|Worth|1876|p=153}}

===Names===
During the seventeenth century, the statue was worshiped by pregnant women and had various names in the [[Breton language]] such as ''Er Groach Couard'', the "Cowardly Old Woman", or as the "Good Woman",{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=89}}{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=101}} ''Groah-Goard'', ''la Couarde'', or ''la Gward''.{{sfn|Macbain|2003|p=91}}{{sfn|Worth|1876|p=152}} The color of the stone from which it was carved also inspired the name ''Gronech Houarn''{{snd}}The Iron Woman.{{sfn|Hare|1896|p=237}} The statue has also been called ''Groah Hoart'' (The Old Guardian).<ref name=pierremerel/>{{sfn|Markale|1999|p=94}} It is said that as the statue stood in the Roman guard house, it was called as ''Hroech-ar-Gouard'', the Old Woman (or Witch) of the Guard-House.{{sfn|Bradshaw|Hughes|1897|p=122}} The inscriptions on the pedestal say that it is called the ''Venus Armoricorum Oraculum''.{{sfn|Bradshaw|Hughes|1897|p=123}}{{sfn|Murray|1864|p=149}} The inscriptions also claim that after the Romans conquered [[Gaul]], it was dedicated to [[Venus Victrix]].{{sfn|Bradshaw|Hughes|1897|p=123}} According to Macquoid, however, the statue could never have been meant to represent a Venus.{{sfn|Macquoid|1877|p=192}}

===Related superstitions and rites===
The statue was an object of superstitious rites in Brittany for centuries.{{sfn|MacCulloch|2010|p=292}} It was believed that sick people would be cured by touching the statue.{{sfn|Trollope|1840|p=386}}{{sfn|Spence|Chapter XIX|p=289}} Childless people would often pay a visit to the statue in the hope of producing offspring.{{sfn|Spence|Chapter XIII|p=381}} It is said that during seventeenth century "foul", "indecent and obscene" rites were also practiced at the statue, and that many couples performed "erotic" acts near the statue.{{sfn|Murray|1864|p=149}}{{sfn|Markale|1999|p=93}}{{sfn|Trollope|1840|p=387}} The statue was also credited with being a [[Magician (paranormal)|sorcerer]] who would help those who approached her with dignity but would avenge herself on those who neglected to treat her with due honour.{{sfn|Markale|1999|p=94}}{{sfn|D'Anvers|Bell|1906|p=166}}

The rituals performed at the statue by pregnant women involved walking round three times, reciting charms and touching one's abdomen. Women would also carry a band which would either be touched to the statue and then tied around their waist, or half of the band would be tied to the statue while the remaining half would be kept on the woman's body until the child was born.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}} After the childbirth, the basin in front of the statue was used by women to bathe in. The rites performed in the honour of the statue were said to be similar to those performed by [[Phoenicia]]ns in the worship of their Venus.{{sfn|Leslie|1866|p=94}}

===Demolition and restoration===
As the statue became an object of a [[Paganism|pagan veneration]], missionaries and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Vannes|Bishop of Vannes]] Charles de Rosmadec asked Claude de Lannion, Lord of Blavet Quinipily, to destroy the statue. In 1661, Lannion ordered the statue to be thrown into the [[Blavet]] river.<ref name=pierremerel>{{cite web|url=http://pierremerel.perso.sfr.fr/bretagne.html#venus|title=La Vénus de Quinipily "Curiosité"|language=French|publisher=pierremerel.perso.sfr.fr|accessdate=6 May 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505003606/http://pierremerel.perso.sfr.fr/bretagne.html|archivedate=5 May 2014}}</ref> Abundant rain destroyed the harvest soon after, which peasantry and devotees interpreted as an act of anger by their insulted idol. In 1664, the statue was drawn from the river and restored to its original location.<ref name=pierremerel/>{{sfn|Worth|1876|p=151}}

In 1670, Rosmadec approached Claude de Lannion again and requested him to break the statue into pieces. Lannion ordered this to be done. However, the workmen, for fear of the peasants and devotees, only mutilated one of her breasts and one arm and again threw the statue into the same river.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}} Soon after this, Claude de Lannion fell from his horse and died, which devotees considered as "a judgement from heaven for his having consented to destroy the idol."{{sfn|Bradshaw|Hughes|1897|p=122}} The statue remained in the river for 25 years until Bishop Rosmadec decided to root out paganism in his diocese and asked Pierre de Lannion, son of Claude de Lannion, to destroy the statue. As Pierre was an [[antiquarian]], he pulled the statue up from the river in 1695 but did not destroy it.{{sfn|Worth|1876|p=152}}<ref name="patrimoine"/> The events associated with the demolition and restoration became a local ''[[cause célèbre]]''.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}}

===Modification and ownership===
In 1696, Pierre de Lannion transported the statue to his [[château]] at Quinipily. It is said that it took forty [[yoke]] of oxen to drag the statue and the large granite basin there. Soldiers posted along the route from Castennec to Quinipily came to blows with peasants furious at the loss of their idol.{{sfn|Worth|1876|p=152}} Residents of Castennec protested against the "abduction" of the statue and with the help of [[Duke of Rohan]] sued Lannion to regain the possession. However, in 1701, the court confirmed the ownership as Lannion's by virtue of his saving it from the river.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}}<ref name=pierremerel/> Supposedly, Pierre damaged the statue during the restoration and secretly replaced it with a new one on a pedestal.{{sfn|Freitag|2004|p=102}}{{sfn|Murray-Aynsley|1900|p=87}}<ref name="patrimoine"/><ref>{{cite book|url=http://members.societe-jersiaise.org/whitsco/aubin1.htm|title=St. Aubin{{snd}}Bishop of Angers (AD 470–550)|last=Hampton|first=Rosemary|publisher=States of Jersey Education Department|publication-place=Jersey|ol=19582300M|publication-date = 1978|accessdate=27 April 2013|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141018114028/http://members.societe-jersiaise.org/whitsco/aubin1.htm|archivedate=18 October 2014}}</ref>

